<SUMMARY>
<!-- PJG ITAG l=10 g=1 f=2 -->
SUMMARY:
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=10 g=1 f=1 -->
 The Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms is 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
proposing to amend regulations to clarify use of the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
designation ``Gamay Beaujolais'' on a wine label. In response 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
to comments from consumers and wine industry members, ATF is 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
proposing that a wine which has been designated with a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
varietal type designation in accordance with 27 CFR 4.23a, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
and which derives not less than 75 percent of its volume from 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Pinot noir grapes or Napa Gamay grapes, may be further 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
designated with the optional term ``Gamay Beaujolais.'' When 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the optional designation ``Gamay Beaujolais'' appears on the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
brand label, it shall be in direct conjunction with the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
required varietal type designation (Pinot noir or Napa Gamay) 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
and appellation of origin, in lettering of substantially the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
same size and kind. ATF believes that this clarification of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the label designation ``Gamay Beaujolais'' will be informative 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
to consumers and industry in the marketing and purchasing of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
such wines. 
