<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The Federal Alcohol Administration Act 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=2 -->
Section 105(e) 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
of the Federal Alcohol Administration Act (FAA Act), 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
27 U.S.C. 205(e), vests broad authority in the Director, ATF, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
as a delegate of the Secretary of the Treasury, to prescribe 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
regulations intended to prevent deception of the consumer, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
and to provide the consumer with adequate information as to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the identity and quality of the product. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Regulations which implement the provisions of section 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
105(e) as they relate to wine are set forth in title 27, Code 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
of Federal Regulations, part 4 (27 CFR part 4). Section 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.23a provides that the name of a single grape variety may be used as the type designation of a grape wine 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
if the wine is labeled with an appellation of origin, and if 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
not less than 75 percent of the wine is derived from grapes 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
of that variety, the entire 75 percent of which was grown in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the labeled appellation of origin area. Section 4.34(b)(1) 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
provides that an appellation of origin disclosing the true 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
origin of the wine shall appear in direct conjunction with 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
and in lettering substantially as conspicuous as the class 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
and type designation if a grape type (varietal) designation 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
is used under the provisions of section 4.23a. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=84 g=1 f=2 -->
History of Gamay Beaujolais Name 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=2 -->
For many years ATF has 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
permitted the use of ``Gamay Beaujolais'' on wine labels as a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
varietal designation. This resulted from the identification 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
in the 1940's, of a grape grown in Napa County, California as 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the Gamay grape native to the Beaujolais region of France. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
In the late 1960's, the University of California at Davis 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(UCD) determined that the grape known as Napa Gamay was the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
true French Gamay and that the Gamay Beaujolais vine was 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
actually a clone of Pinot noir. Since then, ATF has 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
permitted wine produced from both the Napa Gamay and Pinot 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
noir grape varieties to be labeled as ``Gamay Beaujolais.'' 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The Foundation Plant Material Service (FPMS) at UCD (a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
service operated in cooperation with UCD which makes virus 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
free, true type plant material available to the industry) 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
also identified the Gamay Beaujolais vine as a clonal 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
selection of the Pinot noir variety. More recently, UCD determined that the grape known 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
as Napa Gamay is not the Gamay grape of France. Napa Gamay 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
has been positively identified by the FPMS as Valdiguie, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
although it is not widely known by this name. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=84 g=1 f=2 -->
Winegrape Varietal Names Advisory Committee 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=2 -->
In 1982, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
ATF established the Winegrape Varietal Names Advisory 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Committee (referred to as the ``Committee'') to conduct an 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
examination of the hundreds of grape variety names and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
synonyms in use [47 FR 13623, March 31, 1982]. According to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
its charter, the Committee was to advise the Director of the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
grape varieties and subvarieties which are used in the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
production of wine, to recommend appropriate label 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
designations for these varieties, and to recommend guidelines 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
for approval of names suggested for new grape varieties. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Their recommendations were restricted to grape names used in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
producing American wines. The Committee's final report, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
presented to the Director in September 1984, contained the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Committee's findings regarding use of the most appropriate 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
names for domestic winegrape varieties. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
One finding which appeared in the l984 final report of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the Winegrape Varietal Names Advisory Committee was that the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
name ``Gamay Beaujolais'' is not the name of any grape 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
variety. However, the report did recommend that the term be 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
permitted for use during a five year phase out period, for 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
wine made either from the grape called Napa Gamay, or from 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the Gamay Beaujolais clone of Pinot noir. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

