<!-- PJG STAG 4702 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
A number of studies have suggested that ETS exposure adversely affects the myocardial oxygen supply-demand relationship;
this would predispose the heart to develop ischemia or exacerbate preexisting ischemia. Direct or indirect exposure
to tobacco smoke has been shown to increase the hemodynamic determinants of myocardial oxygen demand [Exs. 4&hyph;13,
4&hyph;242] at the same time that it potentially reduces both myocardial oxygen supply and delivery by enhancing
the development of coronary atherosclerosis [Exs. 4&hyph;242, 4&hyph;323], causing coronary vasoconstriction
[Exs. 4&hyph;323, 4&hyph;324] and reducing the oxygen carrying capacity of blood through increased carboxyhemoglobin
levels [Ex. 4&hyph;13]. As a result, fewer red blood cells are available to transport oxygen to the body, and to the
heart muscle itself. To compensate for this reduced oxygen carrying capacity of the blood, the heart must work harder,
for example, by increasing the heart rate. This is an example of one mechanism by which ETS may place even further stress
on the heart by increasing myocardial oxygen demand, precisely at a time when the oxygen delivery capabilities of
the blood are reduced. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
A second mechanism by which ETS may increase myocardial oxygen demand is via the direct effect of nicotine. The nicotine
in ETS may cause an increased resting heart rate and blood pressure in exposed individuals. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
One study examined the effects of ETS on healthy individuals during exercise, and found that healthy individuals
experienced fatigue at lower work levels when exercising in the presence of ETS [Ex. 4&hyph;123]. The authors concluded
that ETS exposure interfered with the heart muscle cells' ability to utilize oxygen for energy production. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Consequently, ETS exposure may have an adverse impact on myocardial metabolism and expose the heart muscle to an increased
susceptibility to injury. These mechanisms of cardiac stress and potential injury to the heart are in agreement with
accepted theories of cardiac injury. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
(d) Acute Heart Effects. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
An acute effect of exposure to ETS is the aggravation of existing heart conditions, such as angina. The National Research
Council (1986) reported, based on the effects of studies by Anderson et al. [Ex. 4&hyph;9] and Aronow et al. [Exs. 4&hyph;14,
4&hyph;16, 4&hyph;17], that angina patients are especially sensitive at carboxyhemoglobin levels between 2 and
4%. Guerin et al. [Ex. 4&hyph;129] report that physiologically adverse effects occur in humans at 2.5% carboxyhemoglobin
blood content. Cumulative carbon monoxide levels, due to ETS that result in such an effect are not uncommon in work
environments [Ex. 4&hyph;129]. Acute exposure to ETS has been reported to increase heart rate, elevate blood pressure,
and increase carboxyhemoglobin levels in both angina patients [Exs. 3&hyph;38, 4&hyph;222] and in healthy subjects
[Exs. 4&hyph;18, 4&hyph;217]. Acute exposure has also been associated with slight changes in blood components thought
to be involved in the pathogenesis of atherosclerosis, such as endothelial cell count, platelet aggregate ratio,
and platelet sensitivity to prostacyclin [Exs. 4&hyph;40, 4&hyph;80]. Many effects of ETS exposure, such as ischemia,
may be additionally aggravated by simultaneous exposure to other compounds, such as solvents [Exs. 3&hyph;446,
4&hyph;99]. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
(e) Chronic Heart Effects. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
The occurrence of coronary heart disease in ETS-exposed nonsmokers has been studied by various epidemiological
researchers [Exs. 4&hyph;85, 4&hyph;120, 4&hyph;122, 4&hyph;138, 4&hyph;139, 4&hyph;142, 4&hyph;148, 4&hyph;154,
4&hyph;191, 4&hyph;277, 4&hyph;295]. Small, but statistically significant (at p &gt; 0.05), increases in coronary
heart disease mortality [Exs. 4&hyph;85, 4&hyph;138, 4&hyph;139, 4&hyph;142, 4&hyph;277] indicate a modest impact
of long-term ETS tobacco smoke exposure on the cardiovascular health of nonsmokers. The relative risks calculated
in these studies ranged from 1.3 to 2.7. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The ability of ETS exposure to induce coronary heart disease has also been studied in animals. Zhu et al. [Ex. 4&hyph;330]
