Ideally, data on the incidence of the diseases of interest in the U.S. population were needed to estimate the number
of cases of disease in employed nonsmokers. Since nationwide incidence data were not available for nonsmokers, several
survey sources were used to estimate the mortality rates for heart disease (Framingham Community Study) [Ex. 4&hyph;108],
and lung cancer (Cancer Prevention Survey conducted by the American Cancer Society) [Ex. 4&hyph;7]. Data on the U.S.
