<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
People contribute millions of particles to the indoor air primarily through the shedding of skin scales. Many of these
scales carry microbes, most of which are short lived and harmless. Clothing, furnishings, draperies, carpets, etc.
contribute fibers and other fragments. Cleaning processes, sweeping, vacuuming, dusting normally remove the larger
particles, but often increase the airborne concentrations of the smaller particles. Cooking, broiling, grilling,
gas and oil burning, smoking, coal and wood generate vast numbers of airborne indoor pollutants in various classifications.

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=81 g=1 f=1 -->
3. Controlling Indoor Air 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Control of pollutants at the source is the most effective strategy for maintaining clean indoor air. However, control
or mitigation of all sources is not always possible or practical. In the case of ETS, this means restricting smoking
to separately ventilated spaces. General ventilation is, therefore, the second most effective approach to providing
acceptable indoor air [Exs. 3&hyph;1061G, 3&hyph;1075J]. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

