<!-- PJG STAG 4702 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
The appendices included with this regulation are intended to be informational and, unless otherwise expressly stated
in this section, are not intended to create any additional obligations not otherwise imposed, or to detract or reduce
any existing obligations.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=1 -->
K. Specific Questions Posed
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
OSHA solicits data, views and comment on all provisions proposed in this notice. The Agency sets forth questions below
to highlight specific areas in the proposal upon which comment is sought.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=81 g=1 f=1 -->
Regulatory Analysis Issues
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(1) Are there any comments on the method used by OSHA to estimate benefits resulting from IAQ provisions of the proposed
standard?
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) Are there studies which document, in quantitative terms, the effectiveness of HVAC maintenance on the decline
of indoor air related ailments?
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) OSHA has estimated a substantial productivity benefit resulting from this proposed standard. What additional
studies and other information are available that demonstrate any effect on productivity?
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(4) OSHA has preliminarily determined that the direct costs of compliance with this standard will not unduly harm
small entities. However, OSHA did not determine how the smoking restrictions in this regulation would affect demand,
and therefore profitability, for establishments which provide services and commodities which would be affected
by the proposal (e.g., restaurants and bars). OSHA requests comments, including empirical data regarding the demand
elasticity of such establishments' patrons who will not be permitted to smoke in the presence of employees.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
If economic feasibility is shown to be an issue for establishments such as bars and restaurants, what alternative
feasible methods of compliance would prevent workers from being exposed to tobacco smoke?
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
What other workplaces have circumstances under which provisions of this standard may not be feasible?
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(5) During renovation and remodelling, what are the specific elements for implementing control measures to minimize
degradation of the IAQ of employees performing such activities and employees in other areas of the building? What
are the unit costs associated with the implementation of each control (capital and labor)?
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(6) Please describe practices in your workplace by providing answers to the following:
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG QTAG 02 -->
<!-- PJG /QTAG -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=15 g=1 f=1 -->
_Describe the business, SIC code number and number of employees in the establishment.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
_What type of ventilation systems are presently being used?
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
_If carbon dioxide monitoring is conducted, how often is it being done and by whom and what are the associated costs?
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
_Does your establishment have a policy on IAQ? When and why was it implemented? What are the major components? How many
employees are affected? What type of costs and cost savings have been associated with such a policy (e.g., operating,
maintenance, retrofitting HVAC systems, property damage due to poor IAQ, employee productivity, cleaning, etc.)?
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
_Is smoking allowed in your establishment? If yes, is it limited to designated smoking areas with separate ventilation?
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=81 g=1 f=1 -->
Scope and Application, Paragraph (a)
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(1) Is it necessary and feasible to extend coverage of the entire standard to industrial facilities as well as nonindustrial
facilities? Why? Why not? Which provisions lend themselves to application to industrial environments?
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) Can coverage of the standard feasibly be extended to some industrial facilities but not others? If so, what characteristics
distinguish those workplaces in which it is feasible or necessary to apply the standard from those in which it is not?
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) The regulation as drafted would require employers generally to prohibit smoking by their customers (such as in
bars, restaurants, and stores) where not already banned by a government entity if employees would be exposed to ETS
from customer smoking. Comment is requested on the appropriateness of this provision, possible alternatives, and
feasibility issues.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=81 g=1 f=1 -->
Definitions, Paragraph (b)
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(1) Is the proposed definition of ``air contaminants'' sufficiently descriptive to inform employers of the hazards
which may adversely affect indoor air quality? If not, what additional information should be included in the definition?
Which elements included in the definition are not reflective of hazards which affect indoor air quality?
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Can employers reasonably be expected to be able to detect the presence of air contaminants, as defined, and determine
whether they present a significant risk of material impairment of employee health? What methods are available to
detect indoor air contaminants? What criteria should be used to evaluate the degree of risk that the presence of air
contaminants pose to employees?
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) Is the proposed definition of ``building systems'' sufficiently descriptive to indicate which systems the employer
must attend to in order to assure acceptable indoor air quality? Are the systems listed in the definition those that
directly affect indoor air quality? If not, why not? What other systems affect indoor air quality that are not specifically
cited in the definition, and how do they influence indoor air quality? How must such systems be maintained and operated
in order to assure adequate indoor air quality?
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) Is the term ``building-related illness'' sufficiently descriptive and inclusive of the medical conditions
that can arise from poor indoor air quality? If not, what other medical conditions should be addressed under the definition
and why? Which conditions listed in the definition, if any, should not be considered as ``building-related illness''
and why?
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
</TEXT>
